Part 1 – Creating tidy data using tidyr

Tuition <- tuition_cost %>%
  pivot_longer(c('2017', '2018', '2019', '2020'), names_to = "Year", values_to = "tuition")

Tuition <-Tuition %>% 
  separate(tuition, into = c("InState", "OutState"), sep = "/", convert = TRUE)

Part 2 – North Carolina Schools

Public <- Tuition %>%
  filter(state == "North Carolina", type == "Public", degree_length == "4 Year")

ggplot(data = Public, mapping = aes(x = Year, y = InState, color = name)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(
       x = "Year",
       y = "Cost in $",
       title = "In-State Tuition for North Carolina"
       ) +
  theme(legend.title=element_blank())

UNC <- filter(Public,grepl("University of North Carolina",name))

ggplot(data = UNC, mapping = aes(x = Year, y = InState, color = name)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs (
        x = "Year",
        y = "Cost in $",
        title = "In-State Tuition for UNC schools"
        ) +
  theme(legend.title=element_blank()) + 
  theme(legend.position="bottom") +
  guides(colour = guide_legend(nrow = 4))

Part 3 – Additional Universities

Colorado <- Tuition %>% 
  filter(state == "Colorado", type == "Public", degree_length == "4 Year")

ggplot(data = Colorado, mapping = aes(x = Year, y = OutState, color = name)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(
       x = "Year",
       y = "Cost in $",
       title = "Out-of-State Tuition for Colorado"
       ) +
  theme(legend.title=element_blank())

South_Carolina <- Tuition %>% 
  filter(state == "South Carolina", type == "Public", degree_length == "2 Year")

ggplot(data = South_Carolina, mapping = aes(x = Year, y = InState, color = name)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(
       x = "Year",
       y = "Cost in $",
       title = "In-State Tuition for South Carolina"
       ) +
  theme(legend.title=element_blank())
